<article contenteditable="true" tabindex="1" class="body-part"><h1>Chris - Testing Heading</h1><h2>dsfafsadf asdfasdfs</h2><h3>asdfsadfasdf</h3><h4>asdfads</h4><h5>asdfasdfasdfa</h5><h6>sadfsadfasdfasdfasd</h6><ul><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">The Time it will close is 1054654322.02234234234</li></ul><ol><li>sadfas</li><li>asdfa</li><ol><li>asdfasdf</li><li>asdfas asfasdfas asdfasdf asdfasdfasdf asdfasdf asdfasdf;lsdkfjsdl;fkj ;laskdfjasd;lfkjasld;fkj l;kjasdf;laskdjf;lk ja;lsdkfjas;ldfkjasd;lfkjasd;flkj ;lkasjdfs;ladkjf ;laksjdf;lasdkjf ;lkajsdf;laskjf;lasdkfjs; lkjas;dlfkjas;dlfkj ;lkasjdf;laskdjf;aslkdjf</li><ol><li>sdasd</li><li>asdf</li><li>asdf</li><li>asdf</li><ol><li>asdfasdf</li><ol><li>sdfasdasdfa</li><ol><li>dfad</li><ol><li>asdf</li><ol><li>asdf</li><ol><li>asdf</li><li><span style="font-weight: lighter;">asdf</span></li></ol></ol></ol></ol></ol></ol></ol></ol></ol><h1>Time</h1><p>I want a nice definition of time.&nbsp; Time is:</p><ul><li>Time is an SI second and fraction relative to&nbsp;<u>Second Zero</u>, i.e. it is a real number.&nbsp; Generally it is recorded as a double value in information systems.</li></ul><ul><li><u>Second Zero</u>&nbsp;is defined as 4000 tropical years, for the year 1970, prior to midnight January 1, 1970.</li></ul><p>Using this approach, all positive Times are within the time frame of human civilization.&nbsp; The Unix epoch is easily determined as a constant whole second relative to Second Zero, since Second Zero is actually relative to that second.</p><p>A negative Time could be suffixed "BT" for Before Time rather than a negative sign.&nbsp;</p><p>Time itself has no translation or so-called correction such as leap seconds since all these relate to a view of time.&nbsp; A&nbsp;<i>date&nbsp;</i>is a view of an instant of time.&nbsp; There are different Date (or Calendar) systems.</p><p>Time should not be referred to as "UTC" or anything other than the proper name "Time":</p><ul><li>we had the time of our life.</li><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">The Time it will close is 1054654322.02234234234</li></ul><h2>Tropical Year</h2><p>We use a tropical year for the "way back" calculation because it is a good representation of an average solar year (The Earth's orbit varies slightly).</p><h2>Calendar Systems</h2><p></p><ul><li>Continue to use Gregorian</li><li>New Civil Calendar:</li><ul><li><span style="background-color: window;">A year consists of 4 quarters.&nbsp; We use Quarters as a basis rather than a season because the Northern and Southern Hemispheres have opposite seasons.&nbsp; A common name should be decided for each Quarter.</span><br></li><ul><li><span style="background-color: window;">FE: First Equinox (Spring in the Northern Hemisphere)</span></li><li>FS: First Solstice (Summer)</li><li>SE: Second Equinox (Fall)</li><li>SS: Second Solstice (Winter)</li></ul></ul></ul><ul><ul><li><span style="background-color: window;">Each quarter consists of 90 days and a Season's Eve day as the last day of a quarter. That brings us to 364 days.</span></li><ul><li>A Day within a season:</li><ul><li>&lt;Quarter&gt; 81, 2022.</li><li>&lt;Month Name&gt; 21, 2022.</li></ul></ul></ul></ul><ul><ul><ul><li>The Season's Eve could be a holiday.&nbsp; It could be referred to as:</li><ul><li>Winter's Eve, 2022 or,</li><li>&lt;Month&gt; 31, 2022.</li></ul></ul></ul></ul><ul><ul><li>The day after the last day of the last season is the New Year's Eve day. That brings us to 365 days. New Year's Eve could be a holiday.&nbsp; It could be referred to as:</li></ul></ul><p></p><ul style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><ul><ul><li><span style="background-color: window;">New Year's Eve, 2022 or</span></li><li>&lt;Month&gt; 32, 2022.</li></ul></ul></ul><p></p><ul><ul><li>A leap year occurs as per the Gregorian Calendar.&nbsp; We could also come up with a more precise average.&nbsp; A Leap Day occurs after a New Year's Eve.&nbsp; It would be nice to be a United Nations holiday. [see World's Day].&nbsp;&nbsp;It could be referred to as:</li><ul><li>Leap Day, 2024</li><li>&lt;Month&gt; 33, 2024.</li></ul></ul></ul><p></p><h2>Earliest Civilization</h2><ul><li>Civilization Name: Mesopotamian civilization</li><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">Period: 3500 BC?500 BC</li><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">Original Location: Northeast by the Zagros mountains, southeast by the Arabian plateau</li><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">Current Location: Iraq, Syria, and Turkey</li><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">Meaning: Land between rivers (ancient Greek)</li><li style="background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;">Major Highlights: First civilization in the world</li></ul><ul></ul><ul></ul></article>